---
import ElevationLayout from '../../layouts/ElevationLayout.astro';
import Hero from '../../components/elevation/Hero.astro';
import Section from '../../components/elevation/Section.astro';
import { getProductBySlug } from '../../lib/products/registry';
import { productJsonLd } from '../../lib/structured-data';

const product = getProductBySlug('agent-governance-starter-kit')!;
const jsonLd = productJsonLd(product, 'https://evoked.dev/products/agent-governance-starter-kit');
---

<ElevationLayout
  title="Agent Governance Starter Kit"
  description="Charter, boundaries, drift thresholds, and accountability for your AI agents. Build governance into the structure from day one. $49 PDF."
  structuredData={jsonLd}
>
  <Hero
    eyebrowParts={["Products", "Governance architecture"]}
    headline="Who governs your agents when you're not watching?"
    metaphor={["Charter. Boundaries. Drift. Accountability."]}
    sub="From day one - not after the first incident."
  />

  <Section marker="FIG · I" heading="Why structure first">
    <p class="lede">
      Most agent governance is reactive. Something goes wrong, then you add a rule.
      The rule fixes the symptom. The structure that produced the symptom stays
      untouched.
    </p>
    <p class="pd-body">
      This kit gives you the five governance layers before the first incident.
      Not because incidents won't happen - they will. Because your response to
      them should be informed by structure, not invented under pressure.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="FIG · II" heading="What you get">
    <div class="pd-features">
      <div class="pd-feature">
        <h3>Charter template</h3>
        <p>Define your agent system's purpose, values, and non-negotiable boundaries in a single document. The foundation every other governance decision builds on.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-feature">
        <h3>Boundary specifications</h3>
        <p>Concrete, testable boundaries for agent behavior. Not principles on a wall - specifications you can verify in code.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-feature">
        <h3>Drift monitoring</h3>
        <p>Thresholds and indicators for detecting when agent behavior moves away from intended boundaries. Drift is gradual. Detection should be continuous.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-feature">
        <h3>Accountability protocols</h3>
        <p>Four-level accountability framework: who notices, who escalates, who decides, who reviews. Clear chains prevent governance gaps.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="FIG · III" heading="The five layers">
    <div class="pd-pillars">
      <div class="pd-pillar">
        <span class="pd-pillar-number">1</span>
        <div class="pd-pillar-body">
          <h3>Charter</h3>
          <p class="pd-pillar-question">"What is this system for - and what is it not for?"</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-pillar">
        <span class="pd-pillar-number">2</span>
        <div class="pd-pillar-body">
          <h3>Boundaries</h3>
          <p class="pd-pillar-question">"Where are the lines - and are they enforceable?"</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-pillar">
        <span class="pd-pillar-number">3</span>
        <div class="pd-pillar-body">
          <h3>Drift detection</h3>
          <p class="pd-pillar-question">"How do we know when behavior has moved from where we set it?"</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-pillar">
        <span class="pd-pillar-number">4</span>
        <div class="pd-pillar-body">
          <h3>Accountability</h3>
          <p class="pd-pillar-question">"When something goes wrong, who acts - and in what order?"</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-pillar">
        <span class="pd-pillar-number">5</span>
        <div class="pd-pillar-body">
          <h3>Authority structure</h3>
          <p class="pd-pillar-question">"Who has the power to change the rules - and what constrains them?"</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="FIG · IV" heading="Who this is for">
    <div class="pd-audience">
      <div class="pd-audience-card">
        <h3>Engineering leads</h3>
        <p>Your agents are making decisions in production. Governance determines whether those decisions stay within bounds you set or bounds they discover.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-audience-card">
        <h3>Founders</h3>
        <p>Building governance into v1 is cheaper than retrofitting it after the first incident report. Start structured. Stay structured.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-audience-card">
        <h3>Compliance teams</h3>
        <p>Need a framework that maps agent behavior to organizational policy. The five-layer model gives you auditable structure.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="FIG · V" heading="Buy the starter kit">
    <div class="pd-purchase">
      <div class="pd-price">$49</div>
      <p class="pd-purchase-lead">PDF download. Govern as many agent systems as you need.</p>
      <p class="pd-free-note">
        Looking for the free version? The
        <a href="https://github.com/lowkey-divine/agent-governance-starter-kit" target="_blank" rel="noopener">open-source starter kit on GitHub</a>
        covers the foundation. This paid version adds detailed implementation
        guidance, worked examples from a production system, and the full
        five-layer framework.
      </p>
      <a
        href={product.stripePaymentLink}
        class="pd-buy-cta"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener"
      >Buy the Starter Kit</a>
      <p class="pd-purchase-fineprint">
        Includes the charter template, boundary specifications, drift monitoring
        thresholds, four-level accountability framework, and authority structure
        guide.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="NOTA · BENE" heading="Go deeper" closing={true}>
    <p class="lede">
      The starter kit gives you governance structure. If you want the full trust
      architecture around it, two doorways from here.
    </p>
    <div class="pd-upsell">
      <a href="/products/trust-architecture-complete" class="pd-upsell-card">
        <h3>The complete bundle</h3>
        <p>All four trust architecture products - Blueprint, Voice, Governance, and Restraint - for $149. Save $47.</p>
        <span class="pd-upsell-link">See the bundle &rarr;</span>
      </a>
      <a href="https://cal.com/cal.com-evoked/discovery-call" class="pd-upsell-card" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <h3>Discovery call</h3>
        <p>Free 30-minute call to discuss your governance architecture and figure out next steps.</p>
        <span class="pd-upsell-link">Schedule &rarr;</span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </Section>
</ElevationLayout>

<style>
  /* Page-local: free/paid disclosure inside the purchase card.
     If 2-3 more product pages use this pattern, promote to
     elevation.css alongside the .pd-* block. */
  .pd-free-note {
    font-family: var(--el-body);
    font-size: clamp(0.8rem, 0.75rem + 0.2vw, 0.9rem);
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--el-text-quiet);
    margin: 0 auto 1.25rem;
    max-width: 50ch;
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--el-rule);
  }
  .pd-free-note a {
    color: var(--el-accent);
    text-decoration: none;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--el-rule);
  }
  .pd-free-note a:hover { border-color: var(--el-accent); color: var(--el-text); }
</style>
